From 5c02297063fe62f1c5f896be2b7979b9f03322e8 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: utzcoz <utzcoz@outlook.com>
Date: Sun, 5 Jul 2026 00:09:28 +0800
Subject: [PATCH 7/7] vr: implement the WebXR browser overlay UI on Linux

The in-headset overlay -- the generic "take off your headset" notification shown
during an immersive session when a permission prompt, capture indicator, or
media-picker dialog appears on the desktop -- was disabled on Linux:
ChromeXrIntegrationClient::CreateVrUiHost returned nullptr because constructing
and driving the UI crashed, and there was no Linux path to composite the overlay
into the OpenXR swapchain. Wire it up, composite it, and fix the issues that
exposed. Everything here is Linux-gated or additive; Windows and Android keep
their existing behavior (their object layouts, mojom callback arity, and code
paths are unchanged -- graphics_delegate_win.{cc,h} in particular is untouched).

Enabling the browser-side UI:

- Select the command-buffer GL bindings on Linux (use_command_buffer =
  is_win || is_linux). The VR UI renderers reach glCreateShader() through
  device/vr/gl_bindings.h; with VR_USE_NATIVE_GL (the previous Linux default)
  that resolved to ui/gl's gl::g_current_gl_context, never made current on the
  VR UI thread, so the first shader compile dereferenced a null raw_ptr.
  VR_USE_COMMAND_BUFFER routes the same calls through gles2_c_lib, which a
  command-buffer GraphicsDelegate drives. graphics_delegate_linux is a
  standalone such delegate: it mirrors the platform-neutral (despite its name)
  graphics_delegate_win pipeline rather than subclassing it, so the Windows file
  stays byte-for-byte unchanged. The WebXR data path is unaffected -- it uses
  gpu::gles2::GLES2Interface directly, not these bindings.

- Allocate the gles2_c_lib thread-local key once on Linux in
  GraphicsDelegateLinux::BindContext(), before first shader use.

- Return VRUiHostImpl from CreateVrUiHost on every platform now that Linux can
  construct it.

- The permission DIALOG is a desktop dialog on every platform; the headset only
  shows the generic kPromptGenericPermission notification. So Linux matches the
  existing Windows behavior.

Compositing the overlay into the OpenXR swapchain (Vulkan binding):

- Add a Vulkan composite pass (embedded SPIR-V): a fullscreen triangle per eye
  alpha-blends (premultiplied, matching the browser's GL blend) the overlay over
  the WebXR content in the swapchain image, sampling each eye's UV sub-rect and
  linearizing the browser's gamma-encoded pixels. Replaces an earlier blit that
  could not alpha-blend and mis-scaled the overlay.

Runtime-owned overlay image -- the core of making prompts visible:

- Previously the browser allocated the overlay SharedImage and the runtime
  imported its DMA-BUF. That works while WebXR is visible (a capture indicator
  over live content) because the concurrent WebXR submit drives the SharedImage
  "produce" that flushes the browser's GL writes to the exported buffer. But a
  permission prompt HIDES WebXR, so nothing drove that produce and the runtime
  sampled an all-zero image -- the prompt never reached the headset, no matter
  the buffer type, usage flags, or GL/Vulkan sync tried.

- Invert the ownership to match how WebXR base-layer images already work: the
  runtime allocates the overlay image (a LINEAR, DMA-BUF-exportable VkImage the
  composite samples), wraps it in a ClientSharedImage, and returns the exported
  handle to the browser via a new optional field on
  ImmersiveOverlay.RequestNextOverlayPose (EnableIf=is_linux; the reply is
  unchanged on other platforms). GraphicsDelegateLinux imports it
  (ClientSharedImage::ImportUnowned) and renders the overlay UI directly into
  it; the runtime composites from its own VkImage. No cross-process produce, and
  the browser's GL write is synchronized (WaitSyncToken + glFinish) before the
  composite, exactly like a base-layer image. The prompt now composites into the
  frame Monado receives whether or not WebXR is visible.

Rendering / crash fixes exposed along the way:

- The permission-prompt panel hangs off the ViewportAwareRoot, whose
  head-tracking Y-rotation flips the panel quads' winding on the GL/Vulkan
  (ANGLE) backend, so back-face culling dropped it (only the background showed).
  Disable culling for these flat 2D panels in UiRenderer::Draw() on Linux.

- Do not hand Blink a drawable frame with no shared image
  (MaybeSuppressImagelessFrameId): in shared-image mode Blink DCHECKs every
  frame_id >= 0 frame carries an image, which the overlay's webxr-hidden frames
  otherwise violate. Demote them to frame_id = -1.

- Do not drop a still-pending ImmersiveOverlay SubmitOverlayTexture reply
  callback when a new overlay submit arrives (which mojo fatally rejects), and
  do not std::move an already-dispatched pending-frame's frame_data twice into
  SendFrameData (a null XRFrameDataPtr deref) -- defer the second GetFrameData
  instead. Both are races the blocking Vulkan composite widens; both Linux-only.

- Guard the overlay frame path against a not-yet-ready GPU context in
  OpenXrApiWrapper::BeginFrame(). GraphicsDelegateLinux declares context_provider_
  ahead of the gl_/sii_ raw_ptrs that alias it, so it outlives them.
